  <mads:note type="source">Smith's Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology, Vol 2, 1867, p. 1114: "Moschion, 
    a tragic and comic poet, mentioned more than once by Stobaeus..."</mads:note>  
  <mads:note  type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "Athenian tragedian, probably 2nd half of 3rd cent. BC,
    known almost solely through quotations by Stobaeus. Titles attested include ‘Telephos and two 
    historical dramas: ‘Themistokles, at the heart of which was probably the naval battle at Salamis,
    following on from Aeschylus' ‘Persians, with the distinction that M. made Themistocles the protagonist
    and ‘The Pheraeans, probably dealing with the death of Alexander [15] of Pherae..." 
    Zimmermann, Bernhard (Freiburg). "Moschion." Brill's New Pauly. Brill, 2010. Brill Online. Tufts University Library. 24 November 2010</mads:note>
